Rating: 4
4 forks with a few changes. I would have to give it a 2 1/2 if as is. As others mentioned, I felt that it was too acidic. To cut the acidity, 1/8 cup of brown sugar and some sea salt (as mentioned by another reviewer) as well as 1/4 cup of half and half. Next time I will add less lemon, maybe 2 tablespoons vs. 3. We also added fennel which we absoulutely love. The flavor in this dish is incredible and it added a little texture to the sauce as well as a slightly sweet flavor which we also felt helped with the acidity. It was excellent with those small changes. I may have been able to add just the half and half, but tried the other reviewers trick first which definitely helped, but still felt that I needed to soften it more, which is why I added the half and half. If you don't have brown sugar, you can try the half and half first and see if it helps. Obviously, everyone's tastes are different, so you might have to play with the proportion of each of the ingredients. Seriously excellent dish with only a few minor changes!

Rating: 3
I made this recipe last night for Valentine's. It was amazing, nevertheless I would like to note some suggested alterations which I tried. The wine does result in an acidic taste which I had to remedy with salt and organic brown sugar (just a 1/4 cup of sugar and salt to taste.) I would bet that using a sweeter white wine would remedy the situation. Another suggestion would be to thicken the sauce once the mussels are out for longer than this recipe calls for. Other than that, we enjoyed our mussels and will make this recipe again!

